Tong’ai and a lesbian women’s group named UNITE. Taking inspiration from “the circle,” a term used to imagine local, national, and global queer communities, Miller shows how everyday people in northwest China are taking part in queer culture and activism while also striving to lead traditionally moral lives in a rapidly changing society. The queer stories in this book broaden our understandings of gender and sexuality in contemporary China and show how taking global queer diversity seriously requires us to de-center Western cultural values, historical experiences, and theoretical perspectives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGay liberation movementzChina. 0aGay peoplezChina. 0aGay rights movementzChina. 0aGayszChina. 0aHomosexualityzChina. 0aSexual minoritieszChina. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aqueer, queer culture, China, lgbtq, lesbian, gay, bisexual, trans, transgender, transsexual, Xi'an, activism, ethnography, Tong’ai, gender, sexuality, politics, CCP, PRC, People's Republic of China, AIDs, HIV.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079130340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197883539940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978835399423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978835399/original  a978-3-11-079130-3  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles